solutions.content:
The idea is to fairly map real ranges.

Each `rand7()` call will be a pointer to some range.

Our ranges of interests are within `[0, 10)`
and there are 10 of them: `[0, 1)`, `[1, 2)`, ... `[9, 10)`. Call them **10 ranges**.

Now problem is `rand7()` can only evenly cover range `[0, 10)` by dividing it into 7 parts: with ranges `[0, 1.42)`, ... `[8.58, 10)` and none of them match our **10 ranges**. However, once chosen some range we can keep on dividing it into 7 parts until it does fall into one of the **10 ranges**. Once it falls into any of them we return corresponding label.
```
class Solution {
public:
    // function to return which of 10 ranges our 
    // real number `x` belongs to
    array <int, 2> f(double x) {
        return {(int)floor(x), (int)ceil(x)};
    }
    int rand10() {
        double x = 10.0, cur = 0.0;
        while (true) {
            cur += x * (rand7() / 7.0);
            double ll = cur - x / 7.0, rr = cur;
            if (f(ll) == f(rr)) // within same range ?
                return (int)ceil(rr);
            x /= 7.0;
            cur -= x;
        }
        return 1;
    }
};
```

Tested expectation for this is close to `~ 2.262`

